The paper proposes an energy-efficient counting rule for distributed detection in wireless sensor networks, which involves transmitting binary decisions from local sensors to a fusion center. This suggests that the paper may belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) or Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper proposes an ordering scheme for sensor transmissions to improve energy efficiency, which involves prioritizing highly informative sensors. This suggests that the paper may also belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) or Machine Learning (cs.MA) sub-categories. Finally, the paper considers the problem of target detection in wireless sensor networks, which involves making decisions based on collected data, suggesting that the paper may also belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category.
